Oracle Date Functions:

Oracle Date & Time Functions – Notes
=====================================
ADD_MONTHS:
-----------
  Purpose: 
      -- Adds a specified number of months to a date.
  Behavior:
      -- If the resulting month has fewer days, Oracle returns the last day of that month.
  Example:
      -- ADD_MONTHS(DATE '2016-02-29', 1)
  Result: 31-MAR-16

CURRENT_DATE :
-------------

  Purpose: Returns the current date and time in the session time zone.
  Note: Depends on the user’s session settings, not the database server.
      SQL> SELECT CURRENT_DATE FROM dual;

CURRENT_TIMESTAMP :
----------------------
  Purpose: Returns the current date and time including fractional seconds and time zone.
    Note: Uses the session time zone.
       SQL> SELECT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP FROM dual;

DBTIMEZONE :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the database time zone.
       SQL> SELECT DBTIMEZONE FROM dual;
  Use Case: Useful when working with global or distributed systems.

EXTRACT :
-----------
    Purpose: Extracts a specific part (YEAR, MONTH, DAY, HOUR, etc.) from a date or timestamp.
    SQL> EXTRACT(YEAR FROM SYSDATE)
    Return Type: NUMBER

FROM_TZ :
-----------
  Purpose: Converts a TIMESTAMP value into a TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE.
        FROM_TZ(TIMESTAMP '2017-08-08 08:09:10', '-09:00')
  Use Case: Required before converting between time zones.

LAST_DAY :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the last day of the month for a given date.
  LAST_DAY(DATE '2016-02-01')
  Result: 29-FEB-16

LOCALTIMESTAMP :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the current date and time as a TIMESTAMP, without time zone info.
  SQL> SELECT LOCALTIMESTAMP FROM dual;
  Note: Uses session time zone but does not display it.

MONTHS_BETWEEN :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the number of months between two dates.
  MONTHS_BETWEEN(DATE '2017-07-01', DATE '2017-01-01')
  Result: 6
  Note: Can return fractional values.

NEW_TIME :
-----------
  Purpose: Converts a date from one time zone to another.
  NEW_TIME(date, 'AST', 'PST')
  Limitation: Supports only predefined time zone abbreviations.
  ⚠️ Deprecated in favor of FROM_TZ + AT TIME ZONE

NEXT_DAY :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the next occurrence of a specified weekday after a given date.
  NEXT_DAY(DATE '2000-01-01', 'SUNDAY')

ROUND (Date) :
-----------
  Purpose: Rounds a date to the nearest unit (MONTH, YEAR, etc.).
  ROUND(DATE '2017-07-16', 'MM')
  Result: 01-AUG-17

SESSIONTIMEZONE :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the current session’s time zone.
  SQL> SELECT SESSIONTIMEZONE FROM dual;

SYSDATE:
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the current database server system date and time.
  SYSDATE 
    Note: Does not include fractional seconds or time zone.

SYSTIMESTAMP :
-----------
  Purpose: Returns the system date and time with fractional seconds and time zone.
  SQL> SELECT SYSTIMESTAMP FROM dual;

TO_CHAR (Date) :
-----------
  Purpose: Converts a DATE or TIMESTAMP to a formatted string.
  TO_CHAR(DATE '2017-01-01', 'DL')
  Use Case: Formatting dates for reports and UI.

TO_DATE :
-----------
  Purpose: Converts a character string into a DATE value.
  TO_DATE('01 Jan 2017', 'DD MON YYYY')
  Important: Format mask must exactly match the input string.

TRUNC (Date) :
-----------
  Purpose: Removes the time portion or truncates a date to a specific unit.
  TRUNC(DATE '2017-07-16', 'MM')
  Result: 01-JUL-17

TZ_OFFSET :
-----------
Purpose: Returns the UTC offset of a given time zone.
TZ_OFFSET('Europe/London')
